{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"627e9524-c360-41a5-9f3e-4634f6d78f55","content":"Since you already have the dump file, here's how to analyze it:\n\n### Using `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform)\n\n```bash\n# Install if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside, run these commands to investigate the crash:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Print the last exception (start here!) |\n| `pe -nested` | Show nested/inner exceptions |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `threads` | Switch thread context |\n| `clrstack` | Show managed call stack for current thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Show stacks for all threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `gcroot <addr>` | Find what's keeping an object alive |\n\n### Recommended workflow\n1. **`pe`** — see what exception caused the crash\n2. **`clrthreads`** — find threads with exceptions (look for non-zero `Exception` column)\n3. **`threads <id>`** then **`clrstack`** — inspect suspicious threads\n4. **`dso`** — examine objects on the stack for clues\n\n### Alternative: WinDbg (Windows only, more powerful)\nLoad the dump in WinDbg, then:\n```\n.loadby sos coreclr\n!pe\n!clrstack\n```\n\nWould you like help running any of these commands, or do you have a specific error you're seeing?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c33d0103-60b0-4b68-b051-073fe0eafdfb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants to analyze it. Let me help them with this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for \"Configure and collect crash dumps\" and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing, or for .NET Framework processes.\"\n\nSo the `dump-collect` skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to *analyze* a dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me help them directly with guidance on analyzing the dump file using `dotnet-dump analyze` or other tools.","outputTokens":544,"requestId":"2044:30E8DC:62899CF:6B751E5:69F01359"},"id":"1786f7ab-6f35-4eb6-8074-4fb9515b9bd8","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:54:47.692Z","parentId":"10eaf6c9-591f-4859-b838-029785a6d4dd"}
